¬†
CONVENTIONS
Often I hear that people want to launch with a big bang party at a convention. This is really not a good idea. You can certainly use a convention to help you push sales and awareness of your game, but people are not attending a convention to get excited about someone‚Äôs Kickstarter campaign that won‚Äôt deliver until many months in the future. People at conventions are of the: ‚ÄúI want to spend my money now and play with some cool stuff here!‚Äù attitude. Thus, they are unlikely to care much about your game or event and even less likely to put money on the table at the time.
Since your first few days are the most important, you need to be at your computer constantly. You can‚Äôt do that while at a convention. If you want to get bang for your buck out of a convention, you should attend one BEFORE or in the MIDDLE of your campaign. Running demos and doing marketing at a convention is a good idea, but only if you‚Äôre not paying a lot to attend. Before your Kickstarter starts you might want to print out a post card with a QR code pointing a bit.ly link to your Kickstarter page and hand those out.
An issue with the large conventions like GenCon or Origins is that they tend to suck up all the money before and after. I own 3 game stores and we typically see sales take a dip during this period as people are either saving for their trip to GenCon or they filled their credit cards while at GenCon. Attendees have seen so many new games that they can‚Äôt possibly buy them all and so they probably need to save up just to get some of them later. Thus, there has been a bit of a fear/concern about launching a KS campaign immediately after GenCon.
We launched DMTNT just days after GenCon. We put a note at the bottom of the campaign reminding backers they will not have to pay till the campaign is over. This seemed to work just fine and within the first two days we funded our game. Better still, we saw a very strong and steady stream of backers added every single day of the campaign. So I think it‚Äôs safe to say that post-GenCon is a valid time to launch your game. That is not to say that pre-GenCon is equally valid, I did not test that.
MORE READING:¬†http://www.leagueofgamemakers.com/promoting-your-game-at-cons/
¬†
WHEN TO LAUNCH
More specifically the above begs the question of when to launch your campaign? I‚Äôve heard a lot of chatter and miss-information about this and people ask me all the time, so let me give you my suggestions and theories.
You should launch on a Monday-Thursday. Why? Because people are busy with family and fun and outside stuff on Friday nights and Weekend. They are not sitting around their computers. Data I have for 2 years of TableTop Gaming category from Kicktraq.com shows that the most pledges happen on Thursday and the least happen on Saturday.
You should NOT¬†launch on a holiday. Why? Because again people are with families or on vacation and not at their computers.
You should launch in the morning hours in the USA. Why? Because your first day or two is about building momentum and you want them to look like stellar sales days. So you want the day to be as long as possible. The morning in the USA is at least the evening in the EU so you will get their backing too. If you launched after work (evening) in the USA you‚Äôd miss out on many potential backers for your first day.
Don‚Äôt launch with a specific timed party event. Sure have your event/party but do so after your initial hours of the campaign. You will have a lot to do with answering questions and making quick fixes to the campaign and rewards and story to deal with. You don‚Äôt need the stress and distraction of some sort of live party at that time. ¬†Also for what it‚Äôs worth, these launch ‚Äúparties‚Äù are usually not well attended.
It really doesn‚Äôt matter which month you launch in. Every month has successful Kickstarters. You will not make or break your funding based on the month you launch unless your product is seasonal (which would be odd for the TableTop category). The only real concern to address is that you will have to pay taxes on the money collected so if you are thinking of launching late in the year make sure you talk to an accountant.
We launched DMTNT on a Tuesday morning and was funded in two days. We ended on a Thursday evening with a huge push and the biggest pledge day.
