									James Mathe on September 27, 2014
									                                

                                
									Reply ‚Üì                                


                            It‚Äôs not a matter of finding the referral source of all traffic. It‚Äôs a matter of finding the sources for those the actually backed. This data is not possible to get through outside sources or urls like you suggest. I know how many people clicked on the BGG banners. That however doesn‚Äôt tell me how many people bought our game from that original source (the ROI).

                        
                    
                    


                

                
                
                        
                        
							
                        
                    
                    
                    
                        
                            
									Joe Morrissey on September 27, 2014
									                                

                                
									Reply ‚Üì                                


                            This is a very strange article for me to read right now. I‚Äôm in the middle of my second week of my Kickstarter campaign and everything you‚Äôre saying, I‚Äôm currently living. This advice is ‚Äúdead‚Äù on‚Ä¶ and I‚Äôm not just saying that because I pretty much decided to do everything James wrote above.
One thing I will say for ‚Äònew people‚Äô starting out and trying to get backers that helped us is we gave away a print and play of the game. We were going to have it at a $5 level, but when I did the research on how much we‚Äôd actually make versus what it could potentially bring in. We‚Äôre a new company. No one has heard of us. It just made since to give it away. 
To get people to pledge at all, we offer the full PnP with all the stretch goals for just a $1. We‚Äôve gotten a lot of great press and comments about it. I‚Äôve also seen a decent amount people (around 20) upgrade from the $1 to the full version of the game or higher. 
We believed that giving it away showed our potential backers that we didn‚Äôt need to hide our game behind a pledge level. We believed it was a fun game and to prove it we gave it to them. We put it out there and are getting a lot of positive feedback from people saying they downloaded it and enjoyed it and backed it. I don‚Äôt have the numbers to say that this helped encourage others to either upgrade or pledge, but I don‚Äôt think it hurt. Something to think about.
Either way, great article as always, James. Thank you.

                        
                    
                    


                
                
                        
                        
							
                        
                    
                    
                    
                        
                            
									James Mathe on September 27, 2014
									                                

                                
									Reply ‚Üì                                


                            It‚Äôs also important to note that 99% of the PnP copies will never get printed. So it‚Äôs not a big deal to give it away. In fact we‚Äôll be giving our PnP of our next campaign (DragonFlame in Nov‚Äô14) away as soon as someone pledges anything at all. Immediately. They can still cancel their pledge and walk away. But we want to get them to take the first step.
I‚Äôm not a big fan in the totally free method as people just download things for free and never touch them ‚Äì cause well it was free. I prefer to retain some value in the thing we‚Äôre giving them. Also we do sell our PnP files on RPGNow.com for years after our release and while they (all combined) only make a few hundred bucks a month for us ‚Äì it is steady income for no work.

                        
                    
                    


                
                
                        
                        
							
                        
                    
                    
                    
                        
                            
